The spectacle which met the eyes of Caesar and his as- tonished soldiers upon their entrance was such as had never been seen before in a Roman camp. There were leafy arbours for dining in, tents floored with fresh cut turf, others screened

’ with ivy to protect them from the sun, or wreathed with branches

of bay, vast quantities of silver plate set out with other prepara- tions for the feast that was to celebrate the Pompeian victory, and much besides that told os aristocratic luxury and the spirit that precedes a fall2.
